    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv. For each file, produce a compact summary (limit lists to top 20 entries):
1) total row count;
2) top 20 unique cmdb_id values with counts;
3) top 20 unique KPI/trace/log name values with counts (use kpi_name for metric.csv, trace_name for trace.csv, log_name for log.csv, and for error_logs.csv use no-name column but list top messages trimmed to 100 chars with counts);
4) the minimum and maximum timestamp in the file converted to UTC datetimes (parse timestamps with pd.to_datetime(..., unit='s', utc=True)).
Additionally, for metric.csv return top 20 (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs with counts to show which component-KPI series exist. Keep all outputs compact (counts and the fields requested only)." }

{
    "analysis": "The previous step loaded and summarized all telemetry files. Key findings: metric.csv and trace.csv cover 19:06–19:30 UTC, while error_logs.csv is concentrated 19:20:31–19:29:49 UTC and contains 374 occurrences of \"failed to get product recommendations\" from frontend. Traces show calls to recommendationservice and productcatalogservice; metrics include cpu/mem/socket/latency/diskio across many services. These observations point to a problem affecting the recommendation path (frontend → recommendationservice) around 19:20–19:29 UTC, but metrics need formal anomaly detection (global thresholds) focused on candidate root-cause services (checkoutservice, currencyservice, emailservice, productcatalogservice, recommendationservice) to confirm which service/KPI exhibits sustained anomalies during the incident window. Next, we must compute global thresholds (P95) per component-KPI across the full metric series (per rule) and then inspect incident-window violations for the candidate services to narrow suspects.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, compute the global P95 threshold for each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) time series using the full available metric.csv (do NOT filter by incident window before computing P95). Then filter metric.csv to the incident window [2024-01-17 19:03:34 UTC, 2024-01-17 19:33:34 UTC]. For only these candidate services: checkoutservice, currencyservice, emailservice, productcatalogservice, recommendationservice, produce a compact table (limit 50 rows) with one row per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) containing: cmdb_id, kpi_name, total_points_in_window, count_above_P95, earliest_timestamp_above_P95 (as UTC datetime, or NA if none), max_value_in_window, global_P95_threshold. Only include rows where total_points_in_window > 0. Sort results by count_above_P95 desc then earliest_timestamp_above_P95 asc. Return the table." }

{
    "analysis": "From the previous metric analysis: a few (small-count) metric anomalies were found across several candidate services (checkoutservice, currencyservice, emailservice) but none showed a large sustained breach during the incident window. The most compelling symptom so far is in error_logs.csv: 374 frontend errors saying \"failed to get product recommendations\" concentrated between 2024-01-17 19:20:31 and 19:29:49 UTC. Traces show series that target recommendationservice and productcatalogservice (trace.to_recommendationservice.*, trace.to_productcatalogservice.*) and trace.from_frontendservice.* series. According to the diagnosis workflow, we should now run focused trace analysis (after computing global thresholds on full trace series) to see whether recommendationservice (or its downstream productcatalogservice) shows elevated error_rate or reduced row_count during the incident window, which would support the frontend error evidence. Metric anomalies alone were weak, so trace and log correlation is required to localize the root cause.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load trace.csv. For each distinct (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute the global P95 threshold of the 'value' field using the full trace.csv (do NOT filter by incident window first). Then filter trace.csv to the incident window [2024-01-17 19:03:34 UTC, 2024-01-17 19:33:34 UTC]. For only trace_name patterns that include any of: 'to_recommendationservice', 'to_productcatalogservice', 'from_frontendservice' produce a compact table (limit 20 rows) with one row per (cmdb_id, trace_name) containing: cmdb_id, trace_name, total_points_in_window, metric_type (set to 'error_rate' if trace_name contains 'error_rate', 'row_count' if contains 'row_count', 'duration' if contains 'duration'), count_above_global_P95 (for error_rate and duration types), count_below_global_P05 (for row_count; compute global P05 from full series), earliest_timestamp_of_anomaly (UTC datetime or NA), max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, global_P95_threshold (for error_rate/duration) and global_P05_threshold (for row_count). Sort rows by count_above_global_P95 (or count_below_global_P05) descending, then earliest_timestamp_of_anomaly ascending. Return only these aggregate columns." }
